                content: `
                    <h2>Step 1: Basic Kidney Function</h2>
                    
                    <div class="learning-text">
                        The kidneys are two bean-shaped organs located on either side of the spine, just below the rib cage. Each kidney is about the size of a fist. The primary function of the kidneys is to filter waste products and excess fluids from the blood, which are then excreted as urine. Every day, the kidneys filter approximately 200 liters of blood, producing about 1-2 liters of urine.
                    </div>

                    <div class="prompt-box">
                        <h4>Self-Explanation Prompt:</h4>
                        <p>In your own words, explain what you just learned about the kidneys. What new information did you gain? How does this connect to what you already knew about the body?</p>
                        <div class="response-area">
                            [In a real learning environment, you would type or speak your explanation here...]
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-response">
                        <h4>Example Self-Explanation:</h4>
                        <p>"I learned that kidneys are relatively small organs but they process a huge amount of blood each day - 200 liters! That's surprising because they only produce about 1-2 liters of urine, which means they must be recycling most of what they filter back into the body. I knew kidneys made urine, but I didn't realize they were constantly filtering our entire blood supply multiple times per day. This makes me understand why kidney disease is so serious - if they can't filter properly, waste builds up in the blood."</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="feedback-box">
                        <h4>System Feedback:</h4>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Great connection!</strong> You successfully identified the surprising ratio between blood filtered (200L) and urine produced (1-2L), and correctly inferred that this means most filtered material is returned to the body.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Excellent inference:</strong> You made an important connection between kidney function and kidney disease by reasoning through what would happen if filtration fails.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-suggestion">
                            <strong>Consider adding:</strong> Why might the body need to filter so much blood? Think about how quickly waste products accumulate from cellular metabolism throughout the body.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-extension">
                            <strong>Extension question:</strong> You mentioned that waste "builds up in the blood" during kidney failure. What specific types of waste do you think accumulate, and how might they affect the body?
                        </div>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                content: `
                    <h2>Step 2: The Nephron - The Kidney's Functional Unit</h2>
                    
                    <div class="learning-text">
                        Each kidney contains approximately one million tiny filtering units called nephrons. A nephron consists of a glomerulus and a tubule. The glomerulus is a cluster of tiny blood vessels where filtration begins - blood pressure forces water and small molecules through the vessel walls. The tubule then processes this filtrate, reabsorbing useful substances like glucose, amino acids, and most water back into the bloodstream, while leaving waste products and excess substances to become urine.
                    </div>

                    <div class="kidney-diagram">
                        <h3>Key Components of a Nephron:</h3>
                        <div class="kidney-parts">
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>Glomerulus</strong>
                                Blood filtering cluster
                            </div>
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>Tubule</strong>
                                Processes the filtrate
                            </div>
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>Collecting Duct</strong>
                                Final urine concentration
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="prompt-box">
                        <h4>Self-Explanation Prompt:</h4>
                        <p>Explain how the nephron works. What's the relationship between filtration and reabsorption? Why is it important that the body reabsorbs substances?</p>
                        <div class="response-area">
                            [Pause here to formulate your explanation...]
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-response">
                        <h4>Example Self-Explanation:</h4>
                        <p>"The nephron works in two main stages. First, the glomerulus acts like a filter that lets small molecules through but keeps blood cells and large proteins in the bloodstream. Then the tubule acts like a selective recovery system - it takes back the valuable things the body needs like water, glucose, and amino acids. This makes sense because the body can't afford to lose important nutrients every time it filters waste. It's like sorting through trash but saving anything useful before throwing the rest away. The glomerulus must use active transport to push the blood through the filter since filtering is hard work. With a million nephrons per kidney, that's a lot of parallel processing happening constantly!"</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="feedback-box">
                        <h4>System Feedback:</h4>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Excellent analogy!</strong> Your comparison of the tubule to "sorting through trash but saving anything useful" effectively captures the selective reabsorption process. Analogies like this help solidify understanding.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Strong conceptual understanding:</strong> You correctly identified that the glomerulus filters based on size (keeping large proteins and blood cells) while the tubule makes selective decisions about what to reabsorb.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-correction">
                            <strong>Let's correct a misconception:</strong> You mentioned that the glomerulus uses "active transport" to push blood through. Actually, the glomerulus uses <strong>passive filtration driven by blood pressure</strong> - no cellular energy is required at this stage. The heart's pumping creates high pressure in the glomerular capillaries, which physically forces water and small molecules through the vessel walls. Active transport comes later, when the tubule selectively reabsorbs specific substances back into the blood.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-extension">
                            <strong>Extension question:</strong> Now that you know filtration is passive (pressure-driven), what do you think happens to filtration rate if someone's blood pressure drops too low?
                        </div>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                content: `
                    <h2>Step 3: Blood Pressure and Kidney Function</h2>
                    
                    <div class="learning-text">
                        The kidneys play a crucial role in regulating blood pressure. They do this in several ways: by controlling the volume of blood (more water retained means higher blood volume and pressure), by releasing the enzyme renin which triggers a cascade that constricts blood vessels, and by producing hormones that affect blood vessel diameter. Conversely, blood pressure affects kidney function - the glomerulus requires adequate blood pressure to filter effectively. This creates a delicate feedback system where the kidneys both respond to and regulate blood pressure.
                    </div>

                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Important Connection:</strong> This is why high blood pressure (hypertension) and kidney disease often occur together. High blood pressure can damage the delicate blood vessels in the kidneys, while damaged kidneys struggle to regulate blood pressure, creating a dangerous cycle.
                    </div>

                    <div class="prompt-box">
                        <h4>Self-Explanation Prompt:</h4>
                        <p>Describe the relationship between kidneys and blood pressure. Why is this a "feedback system"? What could go wrong in this system?</p>
                        <div class="response-area">
                            [Think through the connections before continuing...]
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-response">
                        <h4>Example Self-Explanation:</h4>
                        <p>"This is a feedback system because the kidneys and blood pressure affect each other in both directions. The kidneys can increase blood pressure by retaining water or releasing renin, but they also need good blood pressure to filter blood properly. I can see how this could become a vicious cycle in disease - if your blood pressure is too high, it damages the kidneys' filtering vessels. Then the damaged kidneys can't control blood pressure as well, so it gets even higher, causing more damage. It's like a spiral. This explains why doctors are so concerned about both blood pressure and kidney function, especially in older adults or people with diabetes."</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="feedback-box">
                        <h4>System Feedback:</h4>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Outstanding systems thinking!</strong> Your identification of the "vicious cycle" shows you understand bidirectional causation and feedback loops - a sophisticated concept that many learners miss.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Real-world application:</strong> Connecting this to why doctors monitor both blood pressure and kidney function in at-risk populations (older adults, people with diabetes) demonstrates you're thinking beyond the textbook.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-suggestion">
                            <strong>Consider the mechanism:</strong> You mentioned renin but didn't explain how it increases blood pressure. Think about what happens after renin is released and how it might affect blood vessels.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-extension">
                            <strong>Extension question:</strong> You identified high blood pressure damaging kidneys. What about the reverse - what happens to blood pressure when kidneys fail to retain enough water? How might this cause different problems?
                        </div>
                    </div>
                `
            },
            {
                content: `
                    <h2>Step 4: Beyond Filtration - Other Kidney Functions</h2>
                    
                    <div class="learning-text">
                        While filtration is the kidneys' most well-known function, they perform several other vital roles. The kidneys produce erythropoietin (EPO), a hormone that stimulates red blood cell production in bone marrow. They activate vitamin D, which is essential for calcium absorption and bone health. The kidneys also carefully regulate electrolyte balance, including sodium, potassium, calcium, and phosphate levels. Additionally, they help maintain the body's acid-base balance by excreting hydrogen ions and reabsorbing bicarbonate.
                    </div>

                    <div class="kidney-diagram">
                        <h3>Additional Kidney Functions:</h3>
                        <div class="kidney-parts">
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>üî¥ EPO Production</strong>
                                Stimulates red blood cell creation
                            </div>
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>‚òÄÔ∏è Vitamin D Activation</strong>
                                Essential for bone health
                            </div>
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>‚ö° Electrolyte Balance</strong>
                                Maintains sodium, potassium levels
                            </div>
                            <div class="kidney-part">
                                <strong>üß™ pH Regulation</strong>
                                Controls blood acidity
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="prompt-box">
                        <h4>Self-Explanation Prompt:</h4>
                        <p>Explain why kidney disease causes problems beyond just waste accumulation. How do these additional functions connect to overall health?</p>
                        <div class="response-area">
                            [Consider the broader implications...]
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="example-response">
                        <h4>Example Self-Explanation:</h4>
                        <p>"Now I understand why kidney disease causes so many different health problems! Without EPO, people become anemic because they can't make enough red blood cells - that explains why kidney patients often feel tired and weak. Without vitamin D activation, their bones become weak even if they're getting enough vitamin D from food or sun. The electrolyte problems explain why kidney patients need to watch their diet so carefully - too much potassium could affect their heart rhythm. And if the kidneys can't regulate pH, the blood becomes too acidic, which affects how every protein in the body functions. The kidneys aren't just filters - they're central regulators of multiple body systems."</p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="feedback-box">
                        <h4>System Feedback:</h4>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Exceptional synthesis!</strong> You've integrated multiple kidney functions and explained the consequences of each one failing. This shows you're building a comprehensive mental model.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Cause-and-effect reasoning:</strong> Your explanations trace clear pathways: no EPO ‚Üí no red blood cells ‚Üí anemia ‚Üí fatigue. This causal chain thinking is exactly what self-explanation should develop.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-positive">
                            <strong>Strong concluding insight:</strong> Your final statement that "kidneys aren't just filters - they're central regulators" shows you've moved beyond simple memorization to genuine conceptual understanding.
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feedback-extension">
                            <strong>Extension question:</strong> You mentioned that too much potassium affects heart rhythm. Why would the heart be particularly sensitive to potassium levels? (Hint: Think about how nerve and muscle cells work.)
